      "source": "evaluator",
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, im working on a model and noticed my features have totally different scales. like one is 0-1 and another is 1000-5000. why do i actually need to normalize them before training? does it really matter that much?"
    },
    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You should normalize your features because the model's internal learning process often struggles when different inputs are on vastly different scales, which can cause the optimization algorithm to move too slowly or get stuck in poor local minima. If one feature is 1000-5000 while another is 0-1, the gradient updates for the larger numbers will dominate, making the model biased toward those specific inputs regardless of their actual predictive power. While normalization isn't always strictly required for every single algorithm (some are scale-invariant), it is crucial for most neural networks and gradient-based methods to ensure stable and efficient training. Without it, you might see your model train for a long time with poor convergence, or even fail to learn the correct relationships between your features.",
